go to  http://127.0.0.1:8000/admin/ and login

Check to see that posts/admin.py says this:

# posts/admin.py
from django.contrib import admin

from .models import Post

admin.site.register(Post)

Refresh your browser

Now letâ€™s create our first message board post for our database. Click on the + Add button opposite Posts. Enter your own text in the Text form field.

change your posts/models.py

# posts/models.py
from django.db import models


class Post(models.Model):
    text = models.TextField()

    def __str__(self):
        return self.text[:50]


It will now show the 1st 50 characters in you text field!

change your posts/views.py:

# posts/views.py
from django.views.generic import ListView
from .models import Post


class HomePageView(ListView):
    model = Post
    template_name = 'home.html'


(mb) $ mkdir templates

(mb) $ touch templates/home.html

Update your DIRS in settings.py

change your views.py

# posts/views.py
from django.views.generic import ListView
from .models import Post


class HomePageView(ListView):
    model = Post
    template_name = 'home.html'

# mb_project/settings.py
TEMPLATES = [
    {
        ...
        'DIRS': [os.path.join(BASE_DIR, 'templates')], # new
        ...
    },
]

go to your templates/home.html and change it to this:


<!-- templates/home.html -->
<h1>Message board homepage</h1>
<ul>
  {% for post in object_list %}
    <li>{{ post.text }}</li>
  {% endfor %}
</u


(mb) $ touch posts/urls.py

update your posts/urls.py:

# posts/urls.py
from django.urls import path

from .views import HomePageView

urlpatterns = [
    path('', HomePageView.as_view(), name='home'),
]

Restart the server with python manage.py runserver and navigate to our homepage http://127.0.0.1:8000/ which now lists out our message board posts.

Add some new posts to check and see if everything is working

(mb) $ git init

(mb) $ git add -A

(mb) $ git commit -m 'initial commit'

Change your posts/test

# posts/tests.py
from django.test import TestCase
from .models import Post


class PostModelTest(TestCase):

    def setUp(self):
        Post.objects.create(text='just a test')

    def test_text_content(self):
        post=Post.objects.get(id=1)
        expected_object_name = f'{post.text}'
        self.assertEqual(expected_object_name, 'just a test')

Run your test:
(mb) $ python manage.py test

Upload to Heroku:

(mb) $ heroku login

(mb) $ heroku create

(mb) $ heroku git:remote -a #Insert app name

(mb) $ heroku config:set DISABLE_COLLECTSTATIC=1

(mb) $ git push heroku master

(mb) $ heroku ps:scale web=1


